fields.value: Replication data for: An Empirical Study on the Research and Critical Evaluation Skills of Law Students

dsDescriptionValue.value: Although other researchers have delved into various aspects of legal education, the fundamental analysis of research behavior and the quality of research skills remains somewhat uncharted territory.  There have been assessments of the research skills of incoming law students  and the effectiveness of various research programs,   but little to assess skills and preferences of existing law students. Building on surveys and studies from other disciplines,  this article describes an effort to gather empirical data on law studentsâ€™ legal research practices.  Thirty eight, ABA-accredited schools were included in this study, with a total of 3,599 student responses.  The sample was diverse, representing law schools with organizational characteristics ranging in size, rank, public or private standing, age, and geography.  Both part-time and full-time students were included, as were post-JD students

publicationCitation.value: An Empirical Study on the Research and Critical Evaluation Skills of Law Students by Michelle Wu and Leslie Lee
